{"parse":{"title":"Poet as legislator","pageid":40476642,"revid":857286550,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The theme of <b>poet as legislator</b> reached its <a href=\"/wiki/Grandiosity\" title=\"Grandiosity\">grandiose</a> peak in the <a href=\"/wiki/Romanticism\" title=\"Romanticism\">Romantic era</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> epitomised in the view of the lonely, alienated poet as 'unacknowledged legislator' to the whole world.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>However the concept had a long prehistory in Western culture, with classical figures like <a href=\"/wiki/Orpheus\" title=\"Orpheus\">Orpheus</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Solon\" title=\"Solon\">Solon</a> being appealed to as precedents for the poet's civilising role.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Classical_origins\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Classical origins</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Renaissance_and_Augustan_views\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Renaissance and Augustan views</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Romantic_peaks\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Romantic peaks</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Modernist_irony\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Modernist irony</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Classical_origins\">Classical origins</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Poet_as_legislator&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Classical origins\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Plato\" title=\"Plato\">Plato</a>'s opposition to poets in his ideal Republic was predicated on the contemporary existence of <a href=\"/wiki/Homer\" title=\"Homer\">Homeric</a> expounders who claimed that \"a man ought to regulate the tenour of his whole life by this poet's directions\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Plato only allowed the already censured poet to guide the young, to be an acknowledged legislator at the price of total external control.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Less threatened by the poetic role, the Romans by contrast saw poetry, with <a href=\"/wiki/Horace\" title=\"Horace\">Horace</a>, as primarily pleasing, and only secondarily as instructive.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Renaissance_and_Augustan_views\">Renaissance and Augustan views</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Poet_as_legislator&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Renaissance and Augustan views\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Building the view of the fifteenth century Florentine <a href=\"/wiki/Neoplatonism_in_the_Renaissance\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Neoplatonism in the Renaissance\">Neoplatonists</a> on the poet as seer,<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> however, <a href=\"/wiki/Sir_Philip_Sidney\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sir Philip Sidney\">Sir Philip Sidney</a> developed a more powerful concept of the poet as overtopping the philosopher, historian and lawyer to stand out as \"the monarch...of all sciences.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Such a viewpoint was more or less institutionalised in <a href=\"/wiki/Augustan_literature\" title=\"Augustan literature\">Augustan literature</a>, Johnson's <a href=\"/wiki/Rasselas\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Rasselas\">Rasselas</a> maintaining for example that the poet \"must write as the interpreter of nature and the legislator of mankind\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> \u2013 a fully public, even patriotic role moreover<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Romantic_peaks\">Romantic peaks</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Poet_as_legislator&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Romantic peaks\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>By contrast the Romantic view of the poet as <i>unackowledged</i> legislator emerges at the turm of the century in the writing of <a href=\"/wiki/William_Godwin\" title=\"William Godwin\">William Godwin</a>, with his anarchic view of the poet as \"the legislator of generations and the moral instructor of the world\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>It received its most memorable formulation however in <a href=\"/wiki/Percy_Bysshe_Shelley\" title=\"Percy Bysshe Shelley\">Percy Bysshe Shelley</a>'s 1820 \"<a href=\"/wiki/A_Defence_of_Poetry\" title=\"A Defence of Poetry\">A Defence of Poetry</a>\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> Shelley maintained that, through their powers of imaginative understanding, 'Poets' (in the widest sense, of ancient Greece) were able to identify and formulate emerging socio-cultural trends; and were as a result \"the hierophants of an unapprehended inspiration...the unacknowledged legislators of the world\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Modernist_irony\">Modernist irony</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Poet_as_legislator&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Modernist irony\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The grand claims of the Romantics began to give way in the twentieth century to a more ironic stance<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> \u2013 <a href=\"/wiki/Yeats\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Yeats\">Yeats</a> speaking for his calling in general when he wrote \"We have no gift to set a statesman right\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>What remained of the Shelley claim was to be further diminished by <a href=\"/wiki/Postmodernism\" title=\"Postmodernism\">Postmodernism</a>'s distrust for grand narratives, if not perhaps destroyed entirely.<sup id=\"cite_ref-16\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-16\">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Poet_as_legislator&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"div-col columns column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 22em; -webkit-column-width: 22em; column-width: 22em;\">\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Bard\" title=\"Bard\">Bard</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Christopher_Hitchens\" title=\"Christopher Hitchens\">Christopher Hitchens</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Clerisy\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Clerisy\">Clerisy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Mark_Akenside\" title=\"Mark Akenside\">Mark Akenside</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Matthew_Arnold\" title=\"Matthew Arnold\">Matthew Arnold</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Pushkin\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Pushkin\">Pushkin</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/The_arts_and_politics\" title=\"The arts and politics\">The arts and politics</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/V%C3%A1clav_Havel\" title=\"V\u00e1clav Havel\">V\u00e1clav Havel</a></li></ul></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Poet_as_legislator&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">C. Prendergast ed., <i>Cultural Materialism</i> (1995) p. 222</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Richard Holmes, <i>Dr Johnson and Mr Savage</i> (1994) p. 51</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-back